This is a common issue in .NET 10 because MAUI now enables **edge-to-edge rendering** by default on Android. The window no longer resizes for the keyboard — instead, your app draws behind it and you must react to **window insets**.

## Recommended Fix

In your Android platform code (e.g., `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`), listen for IME insets and apply bottom padding:

```csharp
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;
using Microsoft.Maui;

public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity
{
    protected override void OnCreate(Android.OS.Bundle? savedInstanceState)
    {
        base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

        ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(
            Window!.DecorView.FindViewById(Android.Resource.Id.Content)!,
            new KeyboardInsetsListener());
    }

    private class KeyboardInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
    {
        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
        {
            var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
            var navInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());

            // Use the larger of IME or nav bar bottom inset
            int bottom = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, navInsets.Bottom);
            v.SetPadding(0, 0, 0, bottom);

            return insets;
        }
    }
}
```

Also ensure your `AndroidManifest.xml` still has:

```xml
<activity android:windowSoftInputMode="adjustResize" ... />
```

## Alternative: Opt out of edge-to-edge

If you don't need edge-to-edge, you can disable it in `OnCreate`:

```csharp
protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
{
    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);
    AndroidX.Activity.EdgeToEdge.Disable(this);
}
```

This restores the .NET 9 behavior where `adjustResize` shrinks the window.

## Summary

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|----------|------|------|
| Insets listener | Modern, works with edge-to-edge | More code |
| Disable edge-to-edge | Quick one-liner fix | Loses modern look |

The insets approach is the forward-looking solution and gives you full control over how your chat UI responds to the keyboard.
